ENCFF000ZUR	SE	pass	NA	eGFP	-	eGFP:958|3xFLAG:2057	/targets/JUNB-human/		-	/libraries/ENCLB987PHG/	5696c1df3c741e96ec730314f69c50a9	ChIP-seq	2011-01-27T00:00:00.000000+00:00	17715790	36	released	/biosamples/ENCBS353XCU/	/genetic-modifications/ENCGM227XVM/	/biosample-types/cell_line_EFO_0002067/	K562	/targets/JUNB-human/	-	insertion	tagging	eGFP	/labs/kevin-white/	Recombineering is used for tagging cassettes at either the N or C terminus of the protein. ENCFF000ZUS	SE	pass	NA	eGFP	-	eGFP:95|3xFLAG:131	/targets/HDAC8-human/		-	/libraries/ENCLB184KFA/	7ee1eaab3923f127a43296906a2447d8	ChIP-seq	2011-01-27T00:00:00.000000+00:00	31525566	36	released	/biosamples/ENCBS055CUX/	/genetic-modifications/ENCGM234WZN/	/biosample-types/cell_line_EFO_0002067/	K562	/targets/HDAC8-human/	-	insertion	tagging	eGFP	/labs/kevin-white/	Recombineering is used for tagging cassettes at either the N or C terminus of the protein. The N-terminal cassette has a dual eukaryotic-prokaryotic promoter (PGK-gb2) driving a neomycin-kanamycin resistance gene within an artificial intron inside the tag coding sequence. The selection cassette is flanked by two loxP sites and can be permanently removed by Cre Recombinase-mediated excision. The C-terminal cassette contains the sequence encoding the tag followed by an internal ribosome entry site (IRES) in front of the neomycin resistance gene. In addition, a short bacterial promoter (Gb3) drives the expression of the neomycin-kanamycin resistance gene in E. coli.

ENCFF000ZUB	SE	pass	NA	eGFP	-	eGFP:17|3xFLAG:24	/targets/GATA2-human/		-	/libraries/ENCLB049VVD/	1a7f744b33a6cbd77eb4f014f19e0677	ChIP-seq	2011-01-27T00:00:00.000000+00:00	26098735	36	released	/biosamples/ENCBS746ASY/	/genetic-modifications/ENCGM551ILF/	/biosample-types/cell_line_EFO_0002067/	K562	/targets/GATA2-human/	-	insertion	tagging	eGFP	/labs/kevin-white/	Recombineering is used for tagging cassettes at either the N or C terminus of the protein. The C-terminal cassette contains the sequence encoding the tag followed by an internal ribosome entry site (IRES) in front of the neomycin resistance gene. ENCFF000ZVD	SE	pass	NA	eGFP	-	eGFP:376|3xFLAG:1253	/targets/JUND-human/		-	/libraries/ENCLB197JDY/	97c5019479b18da8739b02190c668d36	ChIP-seq	2011-01-27T00:00:00.000000+00:00	23817388	36	released	/biosamples/ENCBS919IGK/	/genetic-modifications/ENCGM078PYN/	/biosample-types/cell_line_EFO_0002067/	K562	/targets/JUND-human/	-	insertion	tagging	eGFP	/labs/kevin-white/	Recombineering is used for tagging cassettes at either the N or C terminus of the protein. The N-terminal cassette has a dual eukaryotic-prokaryotic promoter (PGK-gb2) driving a neomycin-kanamycin resistance gene within an artificial intron inside the tag coding sequence. The selection cassette is flanked by two loxP sites and can be permanently removed by Cre Recombinase-mediated excision. The C-terminal cassette contains the sequence encoding the tag followed by an internal ribosome entry site (IRES) in front of the neomycin resistance gene. In addition, a short bacterial promoter (Gb3) drives the expression of the neomycin-kanamycin resistance gene in E. coli.

The N-terminal cassette has a dual eukaryotic-prokaryotic promoter (PGK-gb2) driving a neomycin-kanamycin resistance gene within an artificial intron inside the tag coding sequence. The C-terminal cassette contains the sequence encoding the tag followed by an internal ribosome entry site (IRES) in front of the neomycin resistance gene.
